hands_on_practices.solution:
1. In quasi-static equilibrium (QSE), the abundance of ${}^{7}\text{Be}$ satisfies the condition that its production rate equals its destruction rate. In terms of abundances $N_i$:
$$N_{{}^{3}\text{He}}\,N_{{}^{4}\text{He}}\langle\sigma v\rangle_{p}
 \;=\;N_{n}\,N_{{}^{7}\text{Be}}\,\langle\sigma v\rangle_{d}\,.$$
2. Since light‐nuclei abundances $N_{{}^{3}\text{He}},N_{{}^{4}\text{He}},N_n$ are assumed to be unchanged to first order in $\epsilon$, we can solve for the abundance of ${}^{7}\text{Be}$:
$$N_{{}^{7}\text{Be}}\propto\frac{\langle\sigma v\rangle_{p}}{\langle\sigma v\rangle_{d}}
 \propto T_b^{\,\nu_p-\nu_d}\,.$$
3. The final ${}^{7}\text{Li}/\text{H}$ abundance tracks the abundance of ${}^{7}\text{Be}$, so the ratio of the perturbed abundance to the standard one is:
$$\frac{N_{{}^{7}\text{Li}}/N_H}{(N_{{}^{7}\text{Li}}/N_H)_{\rm std}}
 =\Bigl(\frac{T_b}{T_\gamma}\Bigr)^{\nu_p-\nu_d}
 =(1+\epsilon)^{\nu_p-\nu_d}\,.$$
4. The fractional change is this ratio minus one. To first order in $\epsilon$, we use the approximation $(1+x)^a \approx 1+ax$:
$$\frac{\delta(N_{{}^{7}\text{Li}}/N_\text{H})}{(N_{{}^{7}\text{Li}}/N_\text{H})_{std}} = (1+\epsilon)^{\nu_p-\nu_d}-1\approx(\nu_p-\nu_d)\,\epsilon\,.$$
Thus the fractional change is $(\nu_p-\nu_d)\epsilon$.
